Chapter 1
Koren
It was 4:30 in the morning according to the Itaniyan time. Koren hated getting up so early. The main reason was that he had to wake up the rest of his platoon. He silently got out of bed, put on his combat suit, and strapped on his assault vest. From the storage cabinet, he gathered all his gear and carefully picked up a particularly small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with a full set of equipment, including a respirator, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking his ammunition pouch, he quietly left the barracks, his boots making a creaking sound as they stepped on the mud and ice.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a light puff and then opened the door. Over the past week, he had to use every trick in the book to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used an alarm clock because it didn't ring half the time, and the speakers only produced a faint hissing noise.
"Are you going to wake them up now?" Koren turned around and saw Lieutenant Nemich approaching him.
"Yes." Kolon replied.
"What method do you plan to use this time?"
Kolon had not yet answered when the door opened, and Harris, Kres, and several others hurriedly came out, already dressed and ready.
"Good morning," Kres said.
"What woke you up?" Kolon asked.
"First, we really don't want to see what trick you'll use to wake everyone up today," said a soldier named Ravelic. "Second, the first platoon to get up can have breakfast first." "You know how terrible those breakfasts are," he added.
Koren said, "You're right, Sergeant Ravelic." He reached out and pressed the switch. Suddenly, a piercing alarm blared through the barracks. He heard someone shout inside, followed by a flurry of hurried footsteps.
"Oh dear, Valturni," Nemich said. "I thought they should have learned to get up with you by now."
"My new recruits did it," Koren said, pointing at Harris, Cres, and Ravelic. "But then again, their squad leader and platoon sergeant make sure to be up before their soldiers."
A few seconds later, the rest of the company emerged, all dressed and ready. Some of the new recruits looked groggy, while others appeared extremely irritable.
"Good morning everyone," Kongren said cheerfully.
"May I be so bold as to ask, sir, why did you choose to wake us up in such a manner?" one of the assault team members (a corporal) asked.
"Because ordinary alarm clocks are rubbish. And Daybreak never sleeps in," Kongren said.
"Take your personal belongings," Kongren continued. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the company, he had the responsibility to assist Captain Bolatin Shao in supervising and leading the company. "We won't be returning. Sergeants and lieutenants, give yourself and your squad fifteen minutes for final checks and to bring what you need for today."
The members of Exodus Company quickly dispersed. They were part of the Second Group Army's Second Assault Brigade. Before the merger, they were originally two separate companies named Cohort and Dagger. This was a elite unit, and Kongren felt a complex mix of emotions about his promotion to lieutenant for many reasons.
Colin walked side by side with First Rank Commander Nimichi on a brightly lit road within the base. The lights along both sides of the road were powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, which helped them evade enemy bombers. To strike back, Daybreak had already begun using the "Marten" tactics in the air and on the ground.
"A new day, a new mission for Hell's Vanguard," Nimichi said with a dry laugh. "Where are they going to send us this time?"
"Some frontline base outside Ianlos City. We are being sent to support the ground offensive." Colin took a drag on his cigarette as he spoke. He somewhat blamed Crees for getting him hooked on smoking, but thinking about the past year, where they had experienced countless battles, he let it go, so he said nothing.
"Truly unfortunate. The front lines are under pressure," Nimichi murmured. "All the news coming out of here is 'Supporting the War, Assisting Kurgan Frontline'. Why not support the Howland Frontline instead?"
"Well said, brother," Colin said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We'll walk with the First Tank Platoon; we won't have to walk far. Captain Xiao should be there."
"Captain Xiao offered us a ride?" Nimitz asked in some surprise.
"Yes. To be honest, he's not as bad as I imagined. My point is, while he's not great, he's not someone you'd find particularly annoying either."
Kolen raised his thumb and index finger, pressing against the throat mic as he adjusted his backpack. "Exodus company, all units, complete your missions and gather at the west depot. We will depart at 05:00 with the first armor platoon."
Every few seconds, he would receive responses from his sergeants. When they first arrived, Harris, Kres, and Ravik were lower-ranking sergeants. Since their basic training on Earth, the four of them had been good friends. Kolen felt like it was a long time ago that he met them, even though it was less than two years. They were all sergeants now, but after the former squad leader was injured by Daybreak snipers and retired a week ago, Kres had taken over command of the second platoon.
When they reached the depot, Kolen and Nimitz’s eyes fell upon about eight Chronos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members scurried around, making sure their war machines were in perfect condition. Kolen quickly spotted Captain Baltron Xiao, who was talking with the armor platoon commander. As they approached, Captain Xiao glanced at them and came forward, showing no discernible emotion on his usual cold face.
"Lieutenant Nemich … Lieutenant Valterti …"
